I also tried to build it by using `cmake` directly:
```
cd onnxruntime
cmake -DCMAKE_CXX_COMPILER=/usr/bin/arm-linux-gnueabihf-g++-7 -DCMAKE_C_COMPILER=/usr/bin/arm-linux-gnueabihf-gcc-7 -DONNX_CUSTOM_PROTOC_EXECUTABLE=/home/conan/protoc-3.16.0-linux-x86_64/bin/protoc ./cmake
make
```
but again it fails at `Linking CXX executable onnxruntime_test_all`.
Please open CMakeCache.txt and search onnxruntime_LINK_LIBATOMIC, then post the value here.

As a quick fix, you can 
Open CMakeLists.txt, change
```cmake
set(onnxruntime_LINK_LIBATOMIC false)
# We don't need to link libatomic on iOS
if (NOT MSVC AND NOT (CMAKE_SYSTEM_NAME STREQUAL "iOS"))
  include(CheckCXXSourceCompiles)
  set(OLD_CMAKE_REQUIRED_FLAGS ${CMAKE_REQUIRED_FLAGS})
  set(CMAKE_REQUIRED_FLAGS ${CMAKE_REQUIRED_FLAGS} -std=c++11)
  check_cxx_source_compiles("
    #include <atomic>
    int main() {
      return std::atomic<int64_t>{};
    }
  " onnxruntime_HAVE_BUILTIN_ATOMICS)
  if (NOT onnxruntime_HAVE_BUILTIN_ATOMICS)
    set(onnxruntime_LINK_LIBATOMIC true)
  endif ()
  set(CMAKE_REQUIRED_FLAGS ${OLD_CMAKE_REQUIRED_FLAGS})
endif ()
```
to
```cmake
set(onnxruntime_LINK_LIBATOMIC true)
```

Thank you @snnn for your quick answer!

> Please open CMakeCache.txt and search onnxruntime_LINK_LIBATOMIC, then post the value here.

Ok, I got it. conanio/gcc7-armv7 is a x86_64 image, not arm.

I don't know much about conanio/gcc7-armv7. I'm afraid I can't provide much help on that. It is a x86_64 image, so if you don't have a prebuilt protoc and build it from our source tree, you will get one in ARM format. You can't run an ARM binary in an x64_64 docker image. That's why you got the "make[2]: external/protobuf/cmake/protoc-3.16.0.0: Command not found" error. 

But if you want to build onnx runtime in an x64 environment, I suggest you doing it directly in your host OS. Because my crosss-compiling instructions rely on docker. You can't run docker inside docker. And things will get very complicated. It is beyond of my knowledge.   And when you do cross-compiling, like
```
cmake -DCMAKE_CXX_COMPILER=/usr/bin/arm-linux-gnueabihf-g++-7 -DCMAKE_C_COMPILER=/usr/bin/arm-linux-gnueabihf-gcc-7 -DONNX_CUSTOM_PROTOC_EXECUTABLE=/home/conan/protoc-3.16.0-linux-x86_64/bin/protoc ./cmake
```
You must setup a toolchain file for it.  For example:
```
 SET(CMAKE_SYSTEM_NAME Linux)
 SET(CMAKE_SYSTEM_VERSION 1)
 SET(CMAKE_C_COMPILER aarch64-linux-gnu-gcc)
 SET(CMAKE_CXX_COMPILER aarch64-linux-gnu-g++)
 SET(CMAKE_FIND_ROOT_PATH_MODE_PROGRAM NEVER)
 SET(CMAKE_FIND_ROOT_PATH_MODE_LIBRARY ONLY)
 SET(CMAKE_FIND_ROOT_PATH_MODE_INCLUDE ONLY)
 SET(CMAKE_FIND_ROOT_PATH_MODE_PACKAGE ONLY)
```
In the third and forth line, you can use abs paths. But, you will need all these settings. Currently you only set two. 


Or, you may do it in a real ARM docker image(like https://hub.docker.com/r/arm32v7/ubuntu/). You need to figure out which OS your ARM device uses. Then you must use the same OS and same version.  It will be much easier to setup but also much slower. If you don't need to develop onnxruntime and run the build multiple times everyday, I feel the build time is acceptable.

And the link error you reported is more like a compiler bug.

See:
https://github.com/richfelker/musl-cross-make/issues/79
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/46999056/crosscompile-undefined-reference-to-std-atomic-futex-unsigned-base-m-futex

Both of the threads suggest using a newer version of GCC. Therefore I will close this issue now.
